6", "Avoma tentative connect 26 May 2026", "Next Step 1/30/26"], "narrative": "The operational pain is well established but never converted to a financial business case. On the 3 Dec 2025 intro call the buyer quantified scale: '$300-400 million in combined direct and indirect spend managed by a central sourcing team of 9-10 people' (key takeaway, Touchpoint 1), and on 29 Jan ~30-35 total users were sized. Tharun made ROI an explicit decision gate on the 26 Feb AI call: when opting for all three modules 'we want to see what is the return total investment and the return on investment, the integration complexity', and on 26 May reinforced 'cost also matters... end of the day'. Despite pricing being shared on 30 Jan, no ROI/savings model (time saved, compliance-risk reduced, maverick spend recaptured) has been delivered, so the value case remains qualitative. Building and presenting that quantified ROI is a ranked move."}, "champion": {"status": "partial", "sources": ["All 7 Avoma touchpoints", "Avoma tentative connect 26 May 2026", "Task 19 May 2026 (OOO naming manager Reem Alghanem)"], "narrative": "Tharun Chandirasekaran (Sourcing Analyst, self-described super-user and POC) is an active, engaged champion: he drove all 7 touchpoints, produced the requirements checklist, looped in IT (Ryan Anderson) and legal (Chris Klein, Laura McCarthy), and on 26 May proactively reassured 'it's not like we are pursuing this with a different supplier'. However he is a developing champion, not yet a power champion: he lacks budget authority, cannot close on his own ('I'll be providing my feedback to my VP'), and his access to Jackie/COO has not translated into executive engagement. What has developed: deep technical advocacy and continuous communication. What is missing: an executive sponsor relationship and proof he can move Jackie. Out-of-office auto-reply named Reem Alghanem as Tharun's manager \u2014 a potential new thread to develop."}, "competition": {"status": "confirmed", "sources": ["Avoma tentative connect 26 May 2026", "Avoma discovery 12 Dec 2025", "Avoma AI discussion 26 Feb 2026", "SF Competitors__c"], "narrative": "The dominant competitor is the status quo / do-nothing path: on 26 May the project was paused with 100% focus shifted to cost mitigation, and the buyer runs a mature incumbent stack (D365 ERP, Coupa for onboarding/invoicing, Ariba/Blackstone for e-bidding, Power BI for analytics) that they explicitly will not replace ('we're not getting rid of Coupa'). Coupa is a quasi-competitor for the AI/sourcing scope \u2014 on 26 Feb Bikash (Zycus) noted Coupa 'already have the supplier piece... maybe a natural choice', and the buyer is weighing whether to build around Coupa. A two-vendor split is a live alternative: Tharun stated (26 Feb) that if CLM exceeds budget they would 'diversify the project between two different vendors' (one CLM, one sourcing). SAP Ariba is incumbent for e-bidding but not actively being expanded. Zycus wins on the integrated suite + agentic AI (Merlin/Anna) story and the CLM gap no incumbent fills; the wedge is proving ROI to beat do-nothing and avoid the vendor split."}, "identify_pain": {"status": "confirmed", "sources": ["Avoma discovery 12 Dec 2025", "Avoma CLM deep dive 11 Mar 2026"], "narrative": "Pain is specific, multi-sourced and owned by the sourcing team. On 12 Dec Tharun detailed: no contract management tool at all ('we don't house those contracts in any systems'), contracts tracked manually via Word and an online repository (ContractWorks) that is 'pretty primitive... not much insight', renewals/utilization tracked only through custom Power BI, and indirect spend (new since July 2025 after 20-30 acquisitions) is 'a lot fragmented' with no approved vendor list. Reverse auctions are outsourced to Blackstone via email/Excel. The 11 Mar CLM demo confirmed the pain owner's words: negotiation done by 'downloading/uploading Word documents causing version-control delays'. The pain owner is Tharun (so